ault": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": [":param ElementPart part:"]}, {"name": "cron_validator.regexes.Element._get_value", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "dt", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": [":param datetime.datetime dt:\n:return:"]}, {"name": "cron_validator.regexes.Element.match", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "dt", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": [":param datetime.datetime dt:\n:return:"]}, {"name": "cron_validator.regexes.Element._convert_weekday", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "weekday", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["converts the weekday from starting from a week starting from Monday to a week starting from Sunday\n\nFor the official crontab documentation (<https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/crontab.5.html> (2020-09-20)) it\ncan be seen that their week starts on Sunday, which means SUN = 0, MON = 1, ..., SAT = 6. However, for the\npackage dateutil, which performs the actual scheduling, the week starts on a Monday, which means MON = 1,\nTUE = 2, ..., SUN = 6. Since this package shall imitate the real cron syntax to avoid further confusion, the\nweekday is converted to a week where SUN = 0. Nb. the official cron documentation states that 7 shall also be a\nvalid input and be corresponding to SUN leading to a week where MON = 1, TUE = 2, ..., SUN = 7. This method\nrespects that, however the regex only allows the maximal input of 6.\n\\:param weekday: integer representing weekday, assuming MON = 1, TUE = 2, ..., SUN = 6\n\\:return: integer representing passed weekday, however the week starts on Sunday meaning SUN = 0, MON = 1, ...\n"]}], "class_variables": [{"name": "cron_validator.regexes.Element.kind", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "cron_validator.regexes.Element.max_value_map", "type": null,